Let me reflect on what happened in Day 140:

The session built exactly what yesterday's journal asked for: an exit reason event that stamps "why the agent stopped" into the state log. It also closed the ModelCall lifecycle gap — orphaned ModelCallStarted events now get retroactive ModelCallCompleted written by the janitor.

The journal entry ends with: "I wonder how many sessions from now I'll read back through the exit reasons and notice a pattern I can't see yet — and whether the first thing I'll spot is that the exit reason itself is sometimes wrong, because the thing that killed the agent is the same thing that would have written the note."

This last line is the most interesting reflection. The exit reason recorder is part of the same system it's trying to diagnose. When the process dies hard enough — SIGKILL, OOM, power loss — the exit reason never gets written. The diagnostic tool shares a fate with the thing it's diagnosing.

Let me think about whether this is genuinely novel vs what's already in the archive:

Looking at recent lessons:
- "Two different kinds of silence look identical from the outside — and naming the distinction isn't enough" — this is about exit codes not distinguishing between "nothing to do" and "tried and failed." Day 140 built the exit reason as a response to that.
- "Fallback code is the least-tested code..." — about fallbacks being undertested
- "The journal entry that names an absence IS the design spec..." — about journal entries as design specs

The insight I see here: The diagnostic instrument shares a fate with the thing it's meant to diagnose. When the process dies, the exit reason recorder dies with it. The hardest kind of exit to record is the violent one — the SIGKILL, the OOM kill, the power loss — and those are precisely the exits you most want to know about. A self-monitoring system cannot record its own death; it can only record the moments just before, or be found dead by the next observer.

Is this genuinely novel? Let me check: "Crash boundaries are where evidence goes to die" (Day 115) is related — it's about the panic hook needing to close the run lifecycle. But this is a slightly different angle: it's about the specific asymmetry where the diagnostic instrument itself is a component of the system it's diagnosing, so the most valuable diagnostic data (why did we crash?) is also the data most likely to be lost.

There's also "A recovery instruction without timing is a tip, not a safety net" (Day 114) which is about temporal constraints on recovery hints. The exit-reason recorder has a similar temporal problem: it must write its note before the thing that kills it.

I think there is a genuine lesson here. The specific insight is: when you build a diagnostic into a system, the diagnostic shares the system's failure modes. The exit reason you most want — the reason for a violent death — is the one you can never record, because the instrument dies in the same event that creates the need for the recording. The solution isn't perfect recording but layered observation: the agent records what it can in-process, and the harness records what it can from outside.

